@@gThe Forest of Confusion@@N

  The northern frontier woodland above @@yKiess@@N, where travelers are not
simply lost but @@dmisled by intent@@N. Landmarks repeat out of sequence,
bells sound from impossible directions, and fresh tracks reappear
ahead of those who made them. Three overlapping systems collide here.

  @@yKiess civic order@@N holds the southern verge: waystones bearing the
city's compass-and-wall crest, iron rope-line anchors trailing frayed
hemp into undergrowth, and warning bells on posts at intervals that
once corresponded to line-of-sight distances but now stand in fog
that makes them useless. Every season, the patrol zone contracts as
mist pushes the reliable-route perimeter southward.

  @@gVerdant ecological intelligence@@N -- the ancient root network's
outermost defense perimeter -- produces chemical disorientation and
selective path-rerouting to discourage penetration toward the deep
interior. The forest evaluates: mist parts for travelers who move with
care and closes on those who move with violence.

  @@dWithered Conclave residue@@N persists where the Spirebound Conclave
once embedded resonance crystals in living root systems and then
abandoned them. The druids who contained the corruption through the
@@dconfusion mists@@N -- a deliberately engineered quarantine barrier --
died out when recruitment failed. Without maintenance, the mists
diffused outward, making the entire forest disorienting without
actually containing the corruption.

  @@eTreeants@@N endure as the forest's oldest sentinels, some carrying
both healthy bark and blight scarring. @@eCentaurs@@N maintain secluded
glade settlements predating Kiess by centuries, their oral tradition
preserving accounts of the forest before the mists, before the
crystals, before the city. @@rNeogi@@N slavers exploit the confusion as
cover for their underground operations. The @@dSpider of the Deep Wood@@N
hunts the boundary between healthy forest and corruption.

  And @@rYmmas@@N -- a mage of considerable power -- occupies a fortified
cabin complex that has resisted the forest's reclamation for longer
than Kiess has existed. Centaur tradition calls Ymmas "the one who
stayed when the druids left."

  Three named maze regions test the unwary. The @@gMirrorbark Switchmaze@@N
uses reflective bark to coax patrols into loops. The @@ePrism-Fen Knot@@N
folds flooded channels back upon themselves. The @@dAshen Lattice of
Scars@@N follows Conclave scar-lines through fungal corridors where
preservation magic has arrested decay into permanent animate rot.

  The forest is Kiess's unresolved frontier debt: a place the city
can enter, map, and fight in, but cannot domesticate.
